<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>UK FOOD SECURITY</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> FOOD SECURITY</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:3pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A Written Paper submitted by William </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Slinger</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, B.Sc. (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hons</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) Ag.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:3pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:3pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I submit this evidence as an individual farmer. I am also the Chairman and founding Director of Connect Plus Ltd a company formed by farmers to develop and market a local milk brand, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Bowland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Fresh Milk.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:3pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I was co-author of the report “Are UK Farmers in a Common Market?” in 2000, following which in association with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and the Centre for Political and Diplomatic Studies, I helped to host a group of senior agricultural officials/agriculture ministers from the, then, European Union (EU) Candidate Countries of Eastern Europe and the Mediterranean and established first person relations with all the senior agricultural officials/agriculture ministers from those States, comprising Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, The Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Romania, Bulgaria, Turkey, Malta, &amp; Cyprus.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:3pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Subsequently I was consulted by the Curry Commission in respect of their Report and I was invited to, and attended, a conference held in the presence of His Royal Highness The Prince of Wales to review the state of the agricultural sector in respect of supplier’s relationships with the major retailers at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Kendal</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Cumbria</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, 2005</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I was invited by His Royal Highness The Prince of Wales to attend and contribute to a review of the state of the agricultural sector, in the presence of His Royal Highness The Prince of Wales, along with the Secretary of State for the Department for the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Rt</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Hon David </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Milliband</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, and invited others at Keswick, Cumbria, 2007.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:3pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I led a Dairy Value Chain Analysis project team in conjunction with the Food Chain Centre and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Cardiff</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Business</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">School</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> analysing the dairy sector supply chain from farm to end customer which resulted in the production and national publication of “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Bowland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Fresh – Developing Uniquely Differentiated Products</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">–A Case Study”</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:3pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I was invited by His Royal Highness The Prince of Wales to attend and contribute to a review of the state of the agricultural sector, in the presence of His Royal Highness The Prince of Wales, along with the Secretary of State for the Department for the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Rt</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Hon Hilary Benn, MP, Sir Donald Curry and invited others at Kendal, Cumbria, 2008</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">INTRODUCTION</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This paper is structured with the principle points outlined in the executive summary followed by a more general rationale. The two main areas considered are food security issues and recommendations as to how food security might be strengthened in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> can improve its food security, increase its self sufficiency in products for which it has a comparative advantage and remove farmers economic dependence on public subsidy by the introduction of a simple system based on end user pricing.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">End user pricing should be enacted for those commodities which Parliament shall determine appropriate.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">An end user pricing scheme allows the market to set the price which the customer pays for a basic foodstuff as at present. For example with milk a basket of retail milk prices is reviewed quarterly and a set percentage of this average price, as determined by Parliament, sets the minimum farm gate price which the farmer must be paid in the following quarter.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In this way the market sets the price which the customer pays for the particular commodity as at present and Parliament ensures that what it determines to be a fair proportion of what the public has shown that it is prepared to pay is paid to the primary producer in just the same way that a minimum wage was introduced to ensure that those who produce goods or provide services are not themselves paid less than Parliament thinks proper.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This is not a means of propping up the inefficient and as a general rule the farm gate price minimum ought not to exceed average world market prices or the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> would risk undermining its agricultural competitiveness in the long run.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Currently the cost of producing food bears little or no relation to the price which the end customer might have to pay for it since the farmer is unable to pass any increases in the cost of food production on to the processor or the retailer.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The price of food at the farm gate is not determined by the cost of its production but by the price which the processor or retailer can or believes they can obtain it for elsewhere. This fact is a major threat to our food security in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Food and farming supply chains and the current systems of traceability can contribute to increasing our food security resilience in so far as they can demonstrate the integrity of the supply chain and the costs associated with and pertaining to it.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Climate change risks are not in my view accounted for at all when it comes to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> food security.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">For food producers and farmers whether large or small in the food supply chain the principle obstacle to development is generally to be found in the processing sector due to logistics and advances in technology not to mention the huge capital investment now required. This means that it is very nearly impossible for farmers themselves to attempt to access existing markets on anything like a viable scale let alone to access new markets.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A very few farmers may be able to develop new brands and access speciality markets though these markets are so small that they will contribute little or nothing to enhancing the UK’s food security.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Opinions about farming expressed by our leaders and members of the public today are determined by what was happening yesterday and whatever impression they may be under about what might be happening today. What actually is happening today or what we can expect to be happening tomorrow does not shape it.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Food policy ought to be guided towards using resources to provide their optimum outputs which are not necessarily their maximum outputs.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It would be sensible to consider establishing an independent “Committee” or perhaps “Board of Agriculture” as an established “sounding board”. Ideally comprising three individuals from each sector of the industry, for example Wool manufacturers or Sugar </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Beet producers and so forth, and appointed as individuals, not as members of representative organisations, on whom those who may wish to call upon them for independent advice or counsel and do so. For example a Member of the EFRA Committee or a Secretary of State may do so members being available as and when needed or not. In this way agriculture and the food supply chain can provide running snapshot of what is happening and where at any time. It would be a very inexpensive way of benchmarking as required.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Since agriculture is an issue of critical concern to any nation, one of the primary responsibilities of any government is always to ensure the maintenance of a sound and far-sighted agricultural policy.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> must take the long-term outlook into account when approaching the formation of agricultural policy. We must put an end to the present slap-dash “Fire Brigade” approach to dealing with it. The issue is simply too important.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We cannot afford to drop our guard against the relentless tide of new pests and ever developing organisms and diseases and this means ensuring adequate research facilities are available.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Our agriculture is an integral part of national life and makes a real contribution to the general well being, wealth and prosperity of the nation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Britain</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’s agricultural industry must be allowed the freedom to operate in our broadly free market economy, without frequently finding itself rendered economically unviable through no inherent fault of its own. Particularly when Parliament is able to prevent this.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We ought to seek to move agriculture as close as is wise to a truly free market condition.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There are three main reasons why it would be unwise to allow or oblige the agricultural sector to adopt an entirely free market approach. These are:</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) Climatic and seasonal variations which influence the supply of agricultural produce yet bear no relation to market forces whatsoever.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(ii) Because supply might naturally be expected to fall to dangerously close to subsistence level to maintain prices.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(iii) Because given contemporary agricultural regimes elsewhere in the world, we would unilaterally disadvantage our own agricultural industry, with the obviously undesirable effects, political, economic, environmental and social which such a course of action would </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">inevitable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> lead to.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We must ensure that the farmer is able to secure a fair return for producing any commodity in which the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> enjoys a comparative advantage and in which the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is below the level of self sufficiency. If the farmer is able to secure a fair return for such produce in the marketplace, then we ought to be able to save the public a great deal of money in misdirected agricultural support schemes. Losses in transmission of such support are notorious and unnecessary.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">To this end any intervention via subsidy payments, such as may be found necessary, ought to be paid on a uniform basis per unit of output. To do otherwise is to distort the market in a manner that will be unhelpful in the longer term.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The farmer looks for an adequate return on their capital. There is a large enough return to the food sector to provide for all. In the agricultural sector there are around 120,000 vendors all with the same handful of homogenous products to sell, and in effect only a handful of main buyers. Without a limited degree of state supervision, their ability to effectively market produce is always going to be limited.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Governments govern the commercial environment within which the farmer must operate.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In seeking to move closer to a subsidy-free market position we need to recognise the limitations which we unilaterally impose on our own agricultural industry, for example with regard to welfare standards and so forth, when these, quite proper standards, are not required for our farmer’s foreign competitors.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The public is prepared to pay some form of support to those farmers who, through their efforts in maintaining and enhancing some of our more scenic areas and those with an amenity value, contribute to the nation’s well being in respects other than those entirely “market-orientated”. Such support must be entirely de-coupled from production. The level of that support will necessarily be set at a level which the public are prepared to pay for.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">So far as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">agri</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-environmental measures are concerned, a balanced agriculture will always provide the most agreeable and sustainable environment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">So far as young farmers are concerned, there is no point in introducing a new entrant’s scheme if the business has such a low return as to make it unviable in the long term. The best way to attract new entrants is to encourage or set those conditions which will ensure that the industry as a whole can thrive in the longer-term.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In many cases the farmer’s retirement plan has often been formed around their herd, flock or farm business generally. Where the markets have decided these are no longer of much value the possibility of retirement has, for some, become remote or impossible.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Government “help” for the processing and marketing of agricultural products is of limited value. The demand for agricultural produce generally remains the same or increases only slowly over time. Agricultural marketing therefore tends to be in effect a move to increase a share of a particular market, rather than attempting to increase that market. It is especially difficult as agricultural produce has, on the whole, an inelastic demand. When government has effectively acted to prevent farmers working together, such as with the past case of Milk Marque and the DTI inquiry, farmers have found themselves in an impossible situation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Food security is underpinned by the wider rural economy within which farming primarily exists and the necessary levers for promoting rural development already exist. If rural areas have an unsustainable, unviable economy then pouring in more money will not in itself make them sustainable, though it may prop them up for so long as the money continues to be paid. If these same rural areas are economically viable, then again there is no point in pouring in public money where it is not needed. The answer can be found in schemes </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">encouraging economic development by providing factory space and so forth on favourable terms. Economic incentives can also be used. We must define our rural area and then reduce the rate of corporate tax within that stated area, to such a level that it will attract enough businesses to sustain or even strengthen the local economic base. There need be very little direct cost to the taxpayer at all.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">RATIONALE</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The best thing that could be done for food security in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> would be for us to ensure that a fair proportion of the money which the consumer pays for food finds its way back to the producer of that food. If we could achieve that then we might be able to dispense with much if not all the expense and paraphernalia of agricultural support payments and put the public’s money to a more useful purpose, or refrain from taking it off them in the first place.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Agriculture is an issue of critical concern to any nation and one of the primary responsibilities of any government is to ensure the maintenance of a sound and farsighted agricultural policy, of which an adequate supply of safe and affordable food is a major benefit. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Farmers have been burdened with regulation and we have demanded the best standards in welfare and production. In itself this is a laudable aspiration. We undermine our efforts by failing to ensure that the other producers we allow also to supply the markets which our farmers are expected to compete in adhere to the same high standards that farmers in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are rightly expected to adhere to.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’s agricultural industry must be allowed the freedom to operate in what is a broadly free market economy. However it must be allowed to do so without frequently finding itself rendered economically unviable through no inherent fault of its own, in particular where government can prevent it. In particular one which uses resources to provide their optimum outputs, not necessarily their maximum outputs.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">History has shown us that there will be times when farmers are able to derive an adequate return for their produce from the market and times when they are not. Their income can decline to such a degree that it becomes insufficient to sustain their businesses and themselves and their families. We must </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ensure, if we are to expect the calibre of farmers to whom future generations are entitled, that our farmers can expect to receive a fair return for their efforts. The link between effort and reward is and must remain at the centre of all moral societies. It cannot be in anyone’s long term interests that the farmer does not receive a fair return.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If the farmer is able to secure a fair return for produce in the marketplace we ought to be able to save the public a great deal of money in misdirected agricultural support schemes. Losses in transmission of such support are notorious and unnecessary. To this end any intervention via subsidy payments, such as may be found necessary, ought to be paid on a uniform basis per unit of output to do otherwise is to distort the market in a manner which will be unhelpful in the longer term. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It seems that the public are prepared to pay some form of support to those farmers who, through their efforts in maintaining and enhancing some of our more scenic areas and those with an amenity value, contribute to the nation’s well-being in respects other than those entirely “market-orientated”. Such support however must be entirely decoupled from production and the level of that support will necessarily be set at a level which the public are content to pay for.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is no reason why for those products in which we enjoy a comparative advantage this country cannot supply as much of its own needs as it can from our own resources. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Government “help” for the processing and marketing of agricultural products is of limited value. The demand for agricultural produce generally remains the same or increases only slowly over time. Agricultural marketing therefore tends to be in effect a move to increase a share of a particular market, rather than in attempting to increase that market. It is especially difficult as agricultural produce on the whole has an inelastic demand. Where government has effectively acted to prevent farmers working together in a viable manner, such as with the case of Milk Marque and the DTI inquiry, farmers have found themselves in an impossible situation.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Also the form of help offered by government is generally financial when really ideas are what are required and if a diversification scheme is really as viable as it is supposed to be, one has to wonder whether someone wouldn’t have thought of it and be doing that already.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Opinions about farming expressed by our leaders and members of the public today are determined by what was happening yesterday and whatever impression they may be under about what might be happening today. What actually is happening today or what we can expect to be happening tomorrow does not shape it. It will be responsible policy to correct this problem, to facilitate a better decision making process with respect to food and its security of supply.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>